     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "## `std::map` – the “sorted associative container” in C++\n",
      "\n",
      "`std::map` is one of the core containers in the C++ Standard Library.  \n",
      "It stores **key‑value pairs** and guarantees that the keys are always\n",
      "**unique** and **sorted** according to some ordering (by default\n",
      "`std::less<Key>`).  Think of it as a *balanced binary search tree* that\n",
      "lets you look up a value by its key in logarithmic time.\n",
      "\n",
      "Below is a quick‑reference guide followed by a deeper dive.\n",
      "\n",
      "---\n",
      "\n",
      "## Quick Reference\n",
      "\n",
      "| Feature | `std::map` | `std::unordered_map` |\n",
      "|---------|------------|----------------------|\n",
      "| Ordering | Yes (sorted by key) | No (hash‑based) |\n",
      "| Key uniqueness | Yes | Yes |\n",
      "| Typical complexity | `O(log N)` for insert/search/erase | `O(1)` average, `O(N)` worst |\n",
      "| Implementation | Red‑Black tree (balanced BST) | Hash table |\n",
      "| Use‑case | When you need sorted keys or deterministic order | When you need fastest lookup and don’t care about order |\n",
      "\n",
      "> **Tip**: If you don’t need the ordering, `unordered_map` is usually faster.\n",
      "\n",
      "---\n",
      "\n",
      "## Basic Syntax\n",
      "\n",
      "```cpp\n",
      "#include <map>\n",
      "#include <string>\n",
      "#include <iostream>\n",
      "\n",
      "int main() {\n",
      "    // map from string to int\n",
      "    std::map<std::string, int> freq;\n",
      "\n",
      "    // insert\n",
      "    freq[\"apple\"]  = 3;      // operator[]\n",
      "    freq.insert({\"banana\", 5});\n",
      "    freq.emplace(\"cherry\", 2);\n",
      "\n",
      "    // find\n",
      "    auto it = freq.find(\"banana\");\n",
      "    if (it != freq.end())\n",
      "        std::cout << \"banana: \" << it->second << '\\n';\n",
      "\n",
      "    // iterate (in key order)\n",
      "    for (const auto& [key, value] : freq) {\n",
      "        std::cout << key << \" -> \" << value << '\\n';\n",
      "    }\n",
      "\n",
      "    // erase\n",
      "    freq.erase(\"apple\");     // by key\n",
      "    freq.erase(it);          // by iterator\n",
      "\n",
      "    return 0;\n",
      "}\n",
      "```\n",
      "\n",
      "### Key Components\n",
      "\n",
      "| Term | Meaning |\n",
      "|------|---------|\n",
      "| **Key** | The unique identifier used for lookup (`std::string` in the example). |\n",
      "| **Mapped Type** | The value associated with each key (`int`). |\n",
      "| **Pair** | Internally stored as `std::pair<const Key, T>`; the key is `const`. |\n",
      "| **Iterator** | Points to a `value_type` (the pair). |\n",
      "| **Comparator** | `Compare` template parameter (default `std::less<Key>`). Determines ordering. |\n",
      "\n",
      "---\n",
      "\n",
      "## How It Works Under the Hood\n",
      "\n",
      "- `std::map` is typically implemented as a **Red‑Black tree** (a self‑balancing binary search tree).  \n",
      "- Each node stores a key, a value, pointers to left/right children, and a color flag.  \n",
      "- Insertion, deletion, and lookup all run in **O(log N)** time because the tree remains balanced.\n",
      "\n",
      "---\n",
      "\n",
      "## Common Operations & Complexity\n",
      "\n",
      "| Operation | Complexity | Notes |\n",
      "|-----------|------------|-------|\n",
      "| `insert`, `emplace` | `O(log N)` | Returns a pair<iterator, bool>. |\n",
      "| `operator[]` | `O(log N)` (insertion if key absent) | Creates a default‑constructed value if key doesn’t exist. |\n",
      "| `find`, `count` | `O(log N)` | `count` returns 0 or 1 (key uniqueness). |\n",
      "| `erase` (by key) | `O(log N)` | |\n",
      "| `erase` (by iterator) | `O(log N)` | |\n",
      "| `size`, `empty` | `O(1)` | |\n",
      "| Iteration (`begin()` → `end()`) | `O(N)` | Traverses keys in sorted order. |\n",
      "\n",
      "---\n",
      "\n",
      "## Custom Ordering\n",
      "\n",
      "If you need a different ordering (e.g., descending, case‑insensitive, or a custom struct), supply a comparator:\n",
      "\n",
      "```cpp\n",
      "struct CaseInsensitiveCompare {\n",
      "    bool operator()(const std::string& a, const std::string& b) const {\n",
      "        return std::lexicographical_compare(\n",
      "            a.begin(), a.end(),\n",
      "            b.begin(), b.end(),\n",
      "            [](char ca, char cb) { return std::tolower(ca) < std::tolower(cb); });\n",
      "    }\n",
      "};\n",
      "\n",
      "std::map<std::string, int, CaseInsensitiveCompare> ci_map;\n",
      "```\n",
      "\n",
      "---\n",
      "\n",
      "## Frequently Asked Questions\n",
      "\n",
      "| Question | Answer |\n",
      "|----------|--------|\n",
      "| **Can a key be modified after insertion?** | No. The key is `const` in the stored pair, so you must erase and re‑insert if you need to change it. |\n",
      "| **What happens if I insert a duplicate key?** | `insert` will fail (returns `false` in the pair). `operator[]` will overwrite the value. |\n",
      "| **Is `std::map` thread‑safe?** | No. Concurrent reads are fine, but writes need external synchronization. |\n",
      "| **How does `std::map` differ from `std::unordered_map`?** | `unordered_map` uses a hash table, giving average constant‑time operations but no key ordering. |\n",
      "| **What is `std::multimap`?** | Same as `map` but allows duplicate keys. |\n",
      "\n",
      "---\n",
      "\n",
      "## Practical Use‑Cases\n",
      "\n",
      "| Scenario | Why `std::map`? |\n",
      "|----------|-----------------|\n",
      "| **Frequency counter** | Keeps keys sorted for easy reporting. |\n",
      "| **Dictionary / lookup table** | Fast, deterministic order for serialization or debugging. |\n",
      "| **Range queries** | You can use `lower_bound` / `upper_bound` to get all keys in a range. |\n",
      "| **Associative array with custom sorting** | e.g., sorted by string length, custom struct, etc. |\n",
      "\n",
      "---\n",
      "\n",
      "## Example: Range Query\n",
      "\n",
      "```cpp\n",
      "// Get all entries whose keys start with 'b'\n",
      "auto it = freq.lower_bound(\"b\");\n",
      "auto end = freq.upper_bound(\"c\"); // keys < \"c\"\n",
      "\n",
      "for (; it != end; ++it) {\n",
      "    std::cout << it->first << \" -> \" << it->second << '\\n';\n",
      "}\n",
      "```\n",
      "\n",
      "Because the keys are sorted, this is efficient (`O(log N)` to find the start, then linear over the range).\n",
      "\n",
      "---\n",
      "\n",
      "## Summary\n",
      "\n",
      "- `std::map` = **sorted, unique key → value** container.  \n",
      "- Internally a balanced BST → `O(log N)` operations.  \n",
      "- Use it when you need deterministic ordering or range queries.  \n",
      "- For fastest lookup without ordering, switch to `unordered_map`.\n",
      "\n",
      "Happy coding! If you have a specific scenario you’d like to see in code, just let me know.\n"
     ]
    }
